“UKDriverDeaths.csv” gives the monthly totals of car drivers in Great Britain killed or seriously injured 1969 to 1984. (Please note that event of number of killed or injured drivers follow poison distribution with parameter \(\lambda\)).

Using this dataset;

  1. Obtain MLE of \(\lambda\) using bootstrap and estimate the bias and standard error of this estimate.
n <- nrow(data)

lambda.hat <- sum(data$x) / n

B <- 1000
lambda.boot <- numeric(B)

for(i in 1:B){
    index <- sample(n, size=n, replace = T)
    lambda.boot[i] <- sum(data$x[index]) / n 
}

estimate.lambda <- mean(lambda.boot)
SE <- sd(lambda.boot)

bias <- estimate.lambda - lambda.hat
out <- c(lambda.hat, estimate.lambda, SE, bias)
names(out) <- c("lambda.hat","estimated lambda", "Std.Err", "Bias")
out
##       lambda.hat estimated lambda          Std.Err             Bias 
##       1670.30729       1670.05154         20.35034         -0.25575
  1. Use the bootstrap to show the distribution of the sample kurtosis. Besides, what is the standard error and bias of the sample kurtosis computed using the bootstrap?
kurtosis_fnc <- function(x,i){
    n <- length(x)
    sample_krts <- mean((x[i] - mean(x[i]))^4) / var(x[i])^2
    return(sample_krts)
    
}
n <- nrow(data)
B <- 1000

kurtosis <- numeric(B)
sample_kurt <- kurtosis_fnc(data$x)

for(i in 1:B){
    
    index <- sample(n, size=n, replace = T)
    x <- data[index,"x"]
    kurtosis[i] <- kurtosis_fnc(x)
}

est_kurt <- mean(kurtosis)
se_kurt <- sd(kurtosis)
bias_kurt <- (est_kurt - sample_kurt)


hist(kurtosis, col="pink") # the distribution from the bootstrap
abline(v=sample_kurt, col="blue",lwd=4)

result <- c(sample_kurt, est_kurt, se_kurt, bias_kurt)
names(result) <- c("sample", "estimated", "std.error","bias")
result
##      sample   estimated   std.error        bias 
##  3.07133848  3.03277946  0.42498278 -0.03855902
  1. Use the jackknife to show the distribution of the sample skewness. Besides, what is the standard error and bias of the sample skewness computed using the jackknife?
skew <- function(x,i){
    n <- length(x)
    sample_skw <- mean((x[i] - mean(x[i]))^3) / mean((x[i] - mean(x[i]))^2)^(3/2)
    return(sample_skw)
    
}
n <- nrow(data)

Skew <-c()
sample_skew <- skew(data$x)

for(i in 1:n){
    
    Skew[i] <- skew(data$x[-i])
}

est_skew <- mean(Skew)
se_skew <- sqrt((n-1) * mean((sample_skew - mean(Skew))^2))
bias_skew <- (est_skew - sample_skew)*(n-1)


hist(Skew, col="orange") # the distribution from the bootstrap
abline(v=sample_skew, col="blue",lwd=4)

result <- c(sample_skew, est_skew, se_skew, bias_skew)
names(result) <- c("sample", "estimated", "std.error","bias")
result
##     sample  estimated  std.error       bias 
##  0.5344923  0.5344336  0.0008118 -0.0112193
  1. Obtain a 95% bootstrap confidence interval and percentile interval for the variance of killed or injured drivers.

Comment on your results.

alpha <- 0.05
B <- 1000
sample_var <- var(data$x)
n <- nrow(data)

S1 <- S2 <- numeric(B)

for(i in 1:B){
  index1 <- index2 <- sample(1:n, size = n, replace = TRUE)
  S1[i] <- var(data[index1,"x"])
  S2[i] <- var(data[index2,"x"])
}

lower_CI <- (n-1) * mean(S1) / qchisq(1-alpha/2, df=n-1)
upper_CI <- (n-1) * mean(S1) / qchisq(alpha/2, df=n-1)

lower_PI <- quantile(S2, alpha/2)
upper_PI <- quantile(S2, 1-alpha/2)

result <- matrix(c(lower_CI,lower_PI,upper_CI,upper_PI), ncol = 2, dimnames = list(c("Conf.Int","Perc.Int"), c("Lower","Upper")))
result
##             Lower    Upper
## Conf.Int 69283.68 103582.1
## Perc.Int 68189.19 101708.3

OR;

B <- 1000 # bootstrap replicates

variance <- numeric(B)

sample_var <- var(data$x)

for(i in 1:B){
    index <- sample(1:nrow(data), size = nrow(data),replace = TRUE)
    x <- data[index,"x"]
    variance[i] <- var(x)
}

est_var <- mean(variance)
se_var <- sd(variance)
bias_var <- est_var - sample_var


hist(variance, col="lightblue") # the distribution from the bootstrap
abline(v=sample_var, col="red",lwd=4)

out <- c(sample_var, est_var, se_var, bias_var)
names(out) <- c("sample variance", "estimated variance", "std.error", "bias")
out
##    sample variance estimated variance          std.error               bias 
##          83874.507          84195.082           8487.937            320.575
lower <- est_var - qnorm(1-alpha/2, 0,1) * se_var
upper <- est_var + qnorm(1-alpha/2, 0,1) * se_var

cat("95% confidence interval for eruptions is= (", lower, ",", upper, ")")
## 95% confidence interval for eruptions is= ( 67559.03 , 100831.1 )
lower <- quantile(variance, alpha/2)
upper <- quantile(variance, 1-alpha/2)

cat("95% quatile interval for eruptions is= (", lower, ",", upper, ")")
## 95% quatile interval for eruptions is= ( 68382.4 , 100692.5 )

Logistic Regression by using Jackknife

attach(titanic_train2)

coefficients <- matrix(0, nrow = 3, ncol = nrow(titanic_train2)) #create empty matrix
rownames(coefficients) <- c(paste("beta",0:2,sep=""))


for(i in 1:nrow(titanic_train2)){
    for(j in 1:3){
        
        model <-  glm(Survived ~ Sex + Age, family = binomial,  data = titanic_train2[-i,])
        coefficients[j,i] <- as.matrix(model$coefficients[[j]])
        }
}

detach(titanic_train2)
#coefficients
estimated_coefficients <- apply(coefficients, 1, mean)
estimated_coefficients
##        beta0        beta1        beta2 
##  1.277286468 -2.465941174 -0.005425992

b) Compare their accuracy measure (like accuracy, sensitivity, specificity) of 4 different models below to estimate ‘Survived’. (i.e. take Survived as your response variable) with jackknife method.

(NOTE: For jackknifing, don’t use built-in function)

Comment on your results.

  1. \(Y_{Survived} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{Age} + \beta_2 X_{Sex} + \epsilon\)

  2. \(Y_{Survived} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{Age} + \beta_2 X_{Sex} + \beta_3 𝑋_{Age}X_{Sex} + \epsilon\)

  3. \(Y_{Survived} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{Age} + \beta_2 X_{Sex} + \beta_3 X_{Age}^2 + \epsilon\)

  4. \(Y_{Survived} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{Age} + \beta_2 X_{Sex} + \beta_3 X_{Age}^2 + \beta_4 X_{Age}^3+ \epsilon\)

attach(titanic_train2)

models <- list(as.formula(Survived ~ Sex + Age),
               as.formula(Survived ~ Sex * Age),
               as.formula(Survived ~ Sex + poly(Age,2)),
               as.formula(Survived ~ Sex + poly(Age,3)))

accuracy <- matrix(0, ncol = length(models), nrow = nrow(titanic_train2)) #create empty matrix
colnames(accuracy) <- c(paste("model",1:4,sep=""))

predicted <- matrix(0, ncol = length(models), nrow = nrow(titanic_train2)) #create empty matrix
colnames(predicted) <- c(paste("model",1:4,sep=""))


for(i in 1:nrow(titanic_train2)){
    for(j in 1:4){
        
        glm <- glm(models[[j]],  family = binomial, data = titanic_train2[-i,])
        accuracy[i,j] <- performance_accuracy(glm)$Accuracy
    }
}


estimated_accuracy <- apply(accuracy,2,mean)
estimated_accuracy
##    model1    model2    model3    model4 
## 0.7665130 0.7870345 0.7634228 0.7860798

Linear regression by using BOOT

library(boot)

reg.coeffs <- function(x, indices) {
  fit.model <- lm(rating ~ complaints + learning + privileges, x[indices,])
  reg.b0 <- fit.model$coefficients[[1]]  # intercept
  reg.b1 <- fit.model$coefficients[[2]]  # regression coefficient
  reg.b2 <- fit.model$coefficients[[3]]  # regression coefficient
  reg.b3 <- fit.model$coefficients[[4]]  # regression coefficient
  return(c(reg.b0, reg.b1, reg.b2, reg.b3))
}
reg.boot <- boot(attitude, reg.coeffs, 1000)
summary(reg.boot)

c) Suggest 3 different model to estimate “rating” using “complaints”, “learning” and “privileges” as covariates. Compare AIC and Adjusted R-squared values of these 3 models using bootstrap method. (NOTE: For part c, don’t use built-in function for bootstrap)

Comment on your results.

library(stats)

attach(attitude)

models <- list(as.formula(rating ~ complaints + learning + privileges),
               as.formula(rating ~  complaints*learning*privileges),
               as.formula(rating ~ complaints + learning + privileges + learning*privileges),
               as.formula(rating ~ complaints))


AIC <- matrix(0, ncol = length(models), nrow = nrow(attitude))
colnames (AIC) <- c(paste("model",1:4,sep=""))

Adj_Rsquared <- matrix(0, ncol = length(models), nrow = nrow(attitude)) 
colnames (Adj_Rsquared) <- c(paste("model",1:4,sep=""))

n <- nrow(attitude)

for(i in 1:n){
    for(j in 1:length(models)){
        i <- sample(n,n, replace = T)
        model <- lm(models[[j]], data = attitude[i,])
        AIC[i,j] <- AIC(model, k=2)
        Adj_Rsquared[i,j] <- summary(model)$adj.r.squared
    }

}
detach(attitude)

comp_AIC <- as.data.frame(apply(AIC,2,mean))
colnames(comp_AIC) <- c("AIC")


comp_R <- as.data.frame(apply(Adj_Rsquared,2,mean))
colnames(comp_R) <- c("Adjusted R-squared")

result <- cbind(comp_AIC, comp_R)



library(dplyr)
library(kableExtra)

kbl(result) %>%
  kable_classic("striped", full_width = T) %>%
  column_spec(1, bold = T, background = "lavender")%>% 
  row_spec(0, background = "mediumslateblue",bold = T)
